Martin Smith from Anchor Capital discussed the markets with eNCA's Rofhiwa Madzena. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - South Africa’s economic activity slowed down in April, but is still showing growth according to the latest monthly data in the BankservAfrica Economic Transactions Index. The BETI increased by a steady 4.5 percent compared with a year ago, to reach the actual level of 136.1. READ: SA economy | Ramaphosa says positive change is coming It says the standardised nominal value of transactions processed last month reached R1.147-trillion. Bankserve says even though the data suggests that the second quarter of 2022 is off to a steady start, there are several headwinds looming which could potentially derail the economic momentum.